      "t": "p",
      "x": "ACUTE — the neutrophil. The neutrophil is the most prominent inflammatory cell in the first 24 hours of acute inflammation — a point Vila made twice. On a smear you recognize it by nuclear segmentation: three to five lobes joined by thin chromatin strands (hence polymorphonuclear, PMN), with a faintly pink, granulated cytoplasm. An elevated blood count is neutrophilia, the classic finding in acute bacterial infection — but remember it also rises in sterile necrosis, including a myocardial infarct, where there is no organism at all. CQ Neutrophil = 3–5 lobed (PMN), the first-24h cell; neutrophilia = acute bacterial OR sterile necrosis. (acute cell ID)"
