      "t": "p",
      "x": "OVERVIEW. Having mapped the cardinal signs and the cellular events of inflammation in Lecture 3, Vila turned to the chemical mediators that actually carry the signals. The organizing point: mediators are either cell-derived — preformed in granules (histamine, serotonin) or newly synthesized on demand (prostaglandins, leukotrienes, cytokines, nitric oxide) — or plasma-derived, circulating as inactive precursors made by the liver (complement, kinins, coagulation factors). Whatever the source, they share a profile: they act on target cells through specific receptors, they are generally short-lived, and they are tightly regulated — which is precisely what keeps a protective response from becoming a destructive one."
