   "Exome = 1.5–2% of genome, 85% of disease mutations. The exome is only the protein-coding ~1.5–2% of the genome, yet over 85% of known disease-causing mutations live in the exons — so exome sequencing captures most clinically relevant variants at far lower cost than whole-genome (it just misses non-coding variants).",
