      "x": "THE VARIANT MENU. Start with the building blocks. A single-nucleotide variant (SNV) is one base swapped for another; once that variant occurs in at least 1% of the population it earns the name single-nucleotide polymorphism (SNP) — a common population variant rather than a private mutation (there are ~180 SNPs linked to breast cancer alone, which we’ll return to). Insertions and deletions (indels) add or subtract base pairs, typically one to ~10,000. Add copy-number and structural changes (inversions, translocations) and you have the menu."
