      "x": "SANGER — the single-gene gold standard. Reindel called this out as the lecture’s focus. Sanger sequencing (first-generation, developed by Frederick Sanger over 40 years ago) reads one short region of interest — about 300–1000 base pairs — and she stressed it “is a gold standard of sequencing even still today… because of its high accuracy.” It is ideal for a monogenic disease like cystic fibrosis: CFTR has a known sequence, one base change alters the protein, and Sanger confirms it. (You don’t need to memorize the CFTR nucleotides — she said so explicitly; just know it’s one gene, one base.)"
