      "x": "EXOME — the cost-effective compromise. Here is the number that gets tested. The exome — the protein-coding portion — is only ~1.5–2% of the genome, yet over 85% of known disease-causing mutations live in the exons. So exome sequencing captures the great majority of clinically relevant variants while slashing cost and storage versus whole-genome. The trade-off: it can miss pathogenic variants in non-coding regions. Don’t flip the two numbers — 1.5–2% is genome coverage, 85% is the share of disease mutations captured."
