      "t": "p",
      "x": "POLYGENIC vs MONOGENIC. A monogenic disease (CFTR) is one gene, predictable by one test. But Reindel hammered that cancer “is probably not related to just one gene… it’s polygenic” — many variants, each contributing a small amount, interacting with environment and physiology. The ~180 SNPs associated with breast cancer are the clean example: no single SNP decides your fate, but summed across many loci they shift your risk. That is why aggregate measures — polygenic risk scores — exist, rather than a single predictive gene test."
