      "x": "ORGAN FORMATION AND THE NEURAL-CREST THREAD. Across weeks 4–8 the organs take shape — limb buds appear (week 4), the heart loops and septates, the gut tube regionalizes, and the pharyngeal arches build the face, jaw, and neck. The recurring villain when things go wrong is neural crest cell migration: these cells stream from the dorsal neural tube into the craniofacial primordia, the cardiac outflow tract, and the pharyngeal arches, so a single migration failure can co-produce cleft lip/palate, conotruncal heart defects, and face/arch anomalies. Dribin’s memorable anchor for laterality defects was the late Catherine O’Hara’s situs inversus (heart on the right, organs mirror-imaged) — a reminder that even “which side” is set during this window."
