      "t": "p",
      "x": "PROLIFERATION AND BRAKES. First, sustaining proliferative signaling — cancer cells drive their own growth through activated oncogenes, sometimes producing their own growth factors (astrocytomas making PDGF), sometimes via constitutively active receptors (GISTs). Second, evading growth suppressors — bypassing the RB/p53 brakes you met in LO 13.3. Third, resisting cell death — the BCL2/p53 apoptosis-evasion of LO 13.5. IMMORTALITY, BLOOD SUPPLY, SPREAD. Fourth, enabling replicative immortality — normal cells lose telomere repeats with each division and senesce after ~50–70 divisions, but cancer cells upregulate telomerase to rebuild telomeres and divide indefinitely (seen in 85–95% of human cancers). Fifth, inducing angiogenesis — building new blood vessels to feed the tumor. Sixth, activating invasion and metastasis — degrading basement membrane with matrix metalloproteinases to invade and spread. Bonfil drove the stakes home here: most cancer-related deaths are due to metastasis. CQ Cancer cells upregulate telomerase to resist telomere erosion → replicative immortality; MMPs degrade basement membrane → invasion/metastasis (the main cause of cancer death). (immortality + invasion)"
