      "t": "p",
      "x": "OVERVIEW. Checkpoint inhibitors are one immunotherapy arm; the other headline approach is CAR-T cell therapy, which re-engineers the patient’s own T cells to attack cancer. A chimeric antigen receptor (CAR) fuses an antibody-derived antigen-recognition domain to intracellular T-cell signaling domains; later-generation CARs add costimulatory domains for a longer, stronger response. THE WORKFLOW. Remove blood and harvest T cells by leukapheresis; engineer them ex vivo to express a CAR — the first and main target is CD19, present on many hematologic cancers; expand the modified cells in vitro; then reinfuse them into the patient. CAR-T is FDA-approved mainly for hematologic cancers — B-cell ALL in children and young adults, diffuse large B-cell lymphoma, and Hodgkin lymphoma — producing long-term remissions in patients who had no other option. CQ CAR-T: leukapheresis → engineer T cells to express an anti-CD19 CAR → expand → reinfuse; approved for B-ALL, DLBCL, Hodgkin. (CAR-T workflow)"
