      "x": "DIAGNOSIS — SCREEN, CONFIRM, MONITOR. The ELISA is the screening test — enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay, ~99% sensitive, detecting antibodies (a color change means positive). A positive ELISA is confirmed by the Western blot (protein electrophoresis): at least two of three bands — p24, gp41, gp120/160 — must be present for a positive confirmatory result. The viral load (RT-PCR) gives the viral set-point and, used alongside CD4 counts, predicts progression and tracks treatment (rising virus + falling CD4 = adjust therapy; falling virus + rising CD4 = working). CQ HIV labs: ELISA screen (99% sens) → Western blot confirm (≥2 of p24/gp41/gp120-160) → viral load (PCR) set-point + progression/monitoring. (HIV diagnostic tests)"
