      "t": "p",
      "x": "TSS vs SSSS — two toxins, two completely different diseases (flagged). Vila spends real time on this distinction because the mechanisms diverge sharply. Toxic shock syndrome is driven by TSST-1 (S. aureus) acting as a superantigen → a massive cytokine storm (IL-1, IL-2, TNF, IFN-γ) → fever, diffuse erythroderma, hypotension, and multi-organ dysfunction; the classic settings are a surgical wound, nasal packing, or a tampon. (Group A strep can cause a TSS-like picture via its pyrogenic exotoxins SPE-A/SPE-C.) Scalded skin syndrome is mechanistically unrelated: exfoliative toxin A/B cleaves desmoglein-1, the desmosomal protein holding keratinocytes together, producing a superficial epidermal split and skin peeling — mainly in newborns/infants — with no cytokine storm and no shock. The presence or absence of systemic shock is the whole distinction."
