      "x": "STREP SYNDROMES AND RHEUMATIC FEVER — primary, secondary, and the non-suppurative trap. Group A Streptococcus pyogenes sorts its diseases into three buckets. Primary infections are where it normally lives: pharyngitis (the number one), impetigo, erysipelas, and the dreaded necrotizing fasciitis. Secondary infections occur when it spreads to seed sites it doesn’t usually start in, like the endocardium. And the non-suppurative complications are immune-mediated and the highest-yield trap: rheumatic fever and post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis. Rheumatic fever appears 2–3 weeks after pharyngitis, the throat culture is now negative (so you won’t find the organism), and pancarditis — endocarditis, myocarditis, and pericarditis together — is, in Vila’s words, “a very strong criterion.” Her exam template is explicit: a patient had a pharyngitis two-to-three weeks ago and now returns with a new heart murmur → immunologic complication of group A strep. “That kind of connection is the one that you have to do.” She is equally explicit about what NOT to memorize: “do we need to know the Jones criteria? No. But you need to know that strep group A has these complications.” And rheumatic fever “is for the lifetime of the individual.”"
